00:45:20.770 --> 00:45:22.660
Vienna Philharmonic
didn't include

00:45:22.660 --> 00:45:26.620
women in the [INAUDIBLE]
until relatively recently,

00:45:26.620 --> 00:45:30.620
so there are a
lot of throwbacks.

00:45:30.620 --> 00:45:35.260
Their attitude towards Jews
is signally despicable.

00:45:35.260 --> 00:45:38.800
Gustav Mahler who was
born a Jew and a bohemian.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:42.400
In order to become the
conductor of the Vienna

00:45:42.400 --> 00:45:45.820
[? Philharmonic, ?] he had
become Catholic temporarily so

00:45:45.820 --> 00:45:47.860
that he could play music.

00:45:47.860 --> 00:45:49.780
Extraordinary stories.

00:45:49.780 --> 00:45:55.090
You should go to the
Judenplatz in the old city,

00:45:55.090 --> 00:45:57.550
where the Jews were massacred.

00:45:57.550 --> 00:46:01.560
There's a wonderful sculpture
by the British sculptor.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:06.670
A woman-- I forget her name--

00:46:06.670 --> 00:46:14.655
built a concrete sculpture
made of books as a remnant.

00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:21.990
There's one last
thing about Vienna.

00:46:21.990 --> 00:46:31.680
The last 10, 20 years of the
end of that century, Vienna

00:46:31.680 --> 00:46:36.630
underwent one of the
great cultural performance

00:46:36.630 --> 00:46:42.960
spans which we associate
with great cities.

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:52.350
We associate it with
15th century Florence,

00:46:52.350 --> 00:46:55.500
the great painters, the great
sculptors, the Medici family.

00:46:58.500 --> 00:47:01.740
This is a similar
period in the West.

00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:09.240
We have the transference
from 19th century

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:12.660
romantic music to modern music.

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:21.480
Brahms died in 1897.

00:47:21.480 --> 00:47:28.440
Schoenberg lived from 1874
to 1951, Alban Berg from 1885

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:36.960
to 1935, Anton Webern 1852
to 1945, Gustav Mahler

00:47:36.960 --> 00:47:40.680
from 1860 to 1911.

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:42.840
These were the
people who invented

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:48.480
the post-romantic music for us.

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:51.060
You may not like the music.

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:55.800
Amongst them, only Mahlers
are now conventionally played

00:47:55.800 --> 00:48:00.180
by the Boston [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:00.180 --> 00:48:04.380
Very few people play Schoenberg
except in their living rooms.

00:48:08.370 --> 00:48:13.320
[INAUDIBLE] opera is
performed now and then,

00:48:13.320 --> 00:48:14.535
Alban Berg's music.

00:48:17.440 --> 00:48:21.250
But this the significance
of a city, that it

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:25.390
can transform culture
in significant ways.

00:48:25.390 --> 00:48:28.930
Why it happens in cities--

00:48:28.930 --> 00:48:29.780
Austria.

00:48:29.780 --> 00:48:35.770
Vienna was not it economic
after the separation of the--

00:48:35.770 --> 00:48:39.160
no, that took
place-- it was later.

00:48:39.160 --> 00:48:41.650
There are a number of theories
as to why this happened.

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:43.900
Peter Hall, the
British urbanist,

00:48:43.900 --> 00:48:46.240
has written about this
in one of his books.

00:48:50.020 --> 00:48:52.930
There's a sort of culmination
of the coming together

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:58.060
of all of the elements of
good culture in a place.

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:03.310
This despite anti-Semitism,
violent anti-Semitism

00:49:03.310 --> 00:49:06.490
which was taken
over by the Nazis

00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:08.905
when they took over Austria.

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:26.980
It happened in New
York from 1945 to 1970

00:49:26.980 --> 00:49:30.970
with the invention of a number
of new forms of modern art.

00:49:30.970 --> 00:49:36.880
The great painters,
Jackson Pollock and others.

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:42.190
I just mentioned it
because it's something

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:45.790
that is not indulged in.

00:49:45.790 --> 00:49:52.330
Not many cities in the world
grabbed the world by its--

00:49:52.330 --> 00:49:56.050
and it's very
difficult to explain

00:49:56.050 --> 00:50:01.460
what in the history of
Vienna predicted this.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:07.630
It's certainly true that the
great romantic composers--

00:50:07.630 --> 00:50:11.720
Mozart, Haydn, and Beethoven--
spent time in Vienna.

00:50:11.720 --> 00:50:14.260
Their music was
constantly performed.

00:50:14.260 --> 00:50:16.990
People learned to
play the music.

00:50:16.990 --> 00:50:20.425
Wittgenstein's
sister, as an example.

00:50:23.860 --> 00:50:25.900
There were small
groups of philosophy.

00:50:25.900 --> 00:50:29.860
The Vienna Circle, the
philosophers in the 1920s,

00:50:29.860 --> 00:50:31.640
was significant.

00:50:31.640 --> 00:50:35.710
There was music
played in houses.

00:50:35.710 --> 00:50:36.640
People were familiar.

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:47.360
Wittgenstein's father had
a large set of children.

00:50:47.360 --> 00:50:48.950
Three of them committed suicide.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:54.500
They were all musically attuned.

00:50:54.500 --> 00:51:00.110
One of them as a child could,
according to a biography,

00:51:00.110 --> 00:51:02.260
distinguish between--

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:05.900
when a band played
outside their house,

00:51:05.900 --> 00:51:09.050
he could tell what was wrong
with the band's playing.

00:51:09.050 --> 00:51:14.010
He could tell which instruments
were playing the wrong music.

00:51:14.010 --> 00:51:18.170
So there was a culture of
music built into the society.

00:51:18.170 --> 00:51:21.320
I don't know if Freud had
anything to do with music.

00:51:21.320 --> 00:51:25.610
He probably was too
busy with his trying

00:51:25.610 --> 00:51:28.145
to understand the psychic mind.

00:51:31.260 --> 00:51:35.580
So the Vienna story is an art
story of a number of things--

00:51:35.580 --> 00:51:39.600
the move from a feudal to a
liberal to a socialist city

00:51:39.600 --> 00:51:42.210
and then back to a modern city.

00:51:45.770 --> 00:51:48.260
A number of things
that I've touched on.

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:54.290
It's one of the great
cities in history.

00:51:54.290 --> 00:52:00.800
It's the only city which built
a single road to dedicate itself

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:05.090
to a new environment,
economically and socially.

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:10.090
And what else can
one say about Vienna?

00:52:10.090 --> 00:52:13.660
It's still a city which
is remarkably well

00:52:13.660 --> 00:52:16.320
cared for planning-wise.

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:19.840
The deputy mayor had
a staff of something

00:52:19.840 --> 00:52:23.800
like 1,500 people in his
planning transportation

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:24.940
section.

00:52:24.940 --> 00:52:34.120
It has a journey to work,
which is 60%, I think,

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:39.400
in public transportation, 40%
in private transportation.

00:52:39.400 --> 00:52:45.220
It's done very well.

00:52:45.220 --> 00:52:49.090
Barcelona is a smaller
city out on the fringes.

00:52:49.090 --> 00:52:52.720
All of these cities of
course were Roman cities--

00:52:52.720 --> 00:52:55.720
London, Paris,
Vienna, and Barcelona.

00:53:03.730 --> 00:53:08.710
The story of Barcelona,
Cerda, and the ensanche

00:53:08.710 --> 00:53:11.950
is a complicated story and
requires a lot of time,

00:53:11.950 --> 00:53:13.900
so I'll jump very quickly.

00:53:16.410 --> 00:53:21.510
The old city of Barcelona
with its Roman walls

00:53:21.510 --> 00:53:29.140
and then its enlarged walls was
the densest in Europe in 1830.

00:53:29.140 --> 00:53:31.750
It had 300 inhabitants
per hectare.

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:35.385
It was twice the density
of the very dense Paris.

00:53:38.140 --> 00:53:57.190
It suffered from epidemics in
1834, 1854, 1864, and 1870.

00:53:57.190 --> 00:54:05.020
Between 1837 and 1847, average
life expectancy amongst men

00:54:05.020 --> 00:54:11.950
was 38.9 for the rich
and 19.7 for the poor.

00:54:11.950 --> 00:54:14.560
It's difficult to believe
that the average life

00:54:14.560 --> 00:54:17.720
expectancy could be
under 20 years of age,

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:21.790
but if you include the
infant mortality in that,

00:54:21.790 --> 00:54:26.320
infant mortality takes a
large number of deaths.

00:54:35.670 --> 00:54:40.800
So we have the condition
of an old city.

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:53.430
No apparent market for the
wealthy occupying the old city.

00:54:53.430 --> 00:54:58.080
No program is in Paris or
London for the transformation

00:54:58.080 --> 00:55:01.980
of the old city.

00:55:01.980 --> 00:55:04.320
There was no royalty
in Barcelona.

00:55:04.320 --> 00:55:06.120
Royalty was in Madrid.

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:10.770
There was a constant tension
between Barcelona and Madrid.

00:55:10.770 --> 00:55:15.270
In fact, Barcelona claimed
a certain independence

00:55:15.270 --> 00:55:21.190
for Catalonia, and
Catalonia has always

00:55:21.190 --> 00:55:25.780
been stuck between
Spain and France.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:28.990
Perhaps that's why Picasso
comes from Catalonia.

00:55:34.530 --> 00:55:40.070
I want to jump into the
story of the extension.

00:55:46.258 --> 00:55:49.500
The extension is the mark
of one man's thinking.

00:55:52.430 --> 00:55:59.790
It was [INAUDIBLE] Ildefons
Cerda born in 1845--

00:55:59.790 --> 00:56:00.290
sorry.

00:56:00.290 --> 00:56:02.660
1815.

00:56:02.660 --> 00:56:07.220
Decided to study engineering,
and at the age of 19

00:56:07.220 --> 00:56:08.300
went to Madrid--

00:56:08.300 --> 00:56:13.520
he comes from Barcelona,
went to Madrid to study.

00:56:13.520 --> 00:56:18.680
Graduated in 1847.

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:24.320
Enlisted in the national
militia from 1841 to 1848.

00:56:24.320 --> 00:56:28.520
He did projects in cities in
Spain, highways infrastructure

00:56:28.520 --> 00:56:30.980
for the ministry of engineering.

00:56:30.980 --> 00:56:35.120
He developed a powerful
political base in Madrid.

00:56:35.120 --> 00:56:40.610
He returned to
Barcelona in 1849.

00:56:40.610 --> 00:56:44.015
In 1854, the walls
began to be taken down.

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:52.820
Cerda did something
extraordinary.

00:56:52.820 --> 00:56:56.255
He first of all decided to
do research in the old city.

00:57:00.290 --> 00:57:04.760
In volume three of his book
General Themes of Urbanization,

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:13.160
written in 1858, he details
patterns of food consumption,

00:57:13.160 --> 00:57:16.040
compares the old city
with other cities,

00:57:16.040 --> 00:57:20.320
detailed maps, mortality rates.

00:57:20.320 --> 00:57:22.340
He found that the
bourgeois had an average

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:31.270
of 3.6 cubic meters of space,
where the working class only

00:57:31.270 --> 00:57:33.730
had 0.9.

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:35.440
That's four times less.

00:57:41.860 --> 00:57:44.590
Imagine this man going
into the old city

00:57:44.590 --> 00:57:50.020
and doing all of this work.

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:53.050
I don't know what
his ambitions were,

00:57:53.050 --> 00:57:57.670
but this example of
research before plan

00:57:57.670 --> 00:58:01.780
stands as the first
time somebody has

00:58:01.780 --> 00:58:08.200
taken the obligation to
study existing facts,

00:58:08.200 --> 00:58:10.660
especially above poverty.

00:58:10.660 --> 00:58:14.780
Remember that Booth's
map in London was 1789.

00:58:14.780 --> 00:58:15.280
No.

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:17.800
1879.

00:58:17.800 --> 00:58:19.990
This was before
Booth's map of London.

00:58:26.620 --> 00:58:29.170
This is not Engels
studying Manchester.

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:36.280
[INAUDIBLE] studied
Manchester partly

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:41.320
to gather the facts on which to
base a large universal theory

00:58:41.320 --> 00:58:43.850
of society.

00:58:43.850 --> 00:58:49.480
It's unclear what
Cerda was doing.

00:58:49.480 --> 00:58:52.150
He just wanted to know facts.

00:58:52.150 --> 00:58:54.430
He wanted to know reality.

00:58:54.430 --> 00:58:55.870
He had no large theory.

00:58:55.870 --> 00:58:57.730
Apparently he didn't have.

00:59:02.890 --> 00:59:13.960
In 1859, there was a
competition for designing

00:59:13.960 --> 00:59:20.140
a plan outside the old city.

00:59:20.140 --> 00:59:29.250
Cerda and a man
called Rovira i Trias

00:59:29.250 --> 00:59:34.050
competed for the final
of architects in general.

00:59:34.050 --> 00:59:37.800
And most of the
people of Barcelona

00:59:37.800 --> 00:59:41.100
preferred Rovira i Trias's plan.

00:59:41.100 --> 00:59:46.560
Rovira i Trias took the old
city as the center, created

00:59:46.560 --> 00:59:50.720
the [INAUDIBLE]
[? republica ?] north of it,

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:55.800
and from that point radiated
out five avenues out

00:59:55.800 --> 00:59:58.330
to the perimeter.

00:59:58.330 --> 01:00:05.990
This is a neoclassical plan
which was relatively common

01:00:05.990 --> 01:00:07.400
in city expansion.

01:00:10.070 --> 01:00:17.540
Cerda's plan was a series of
113 meters by 113 meters blocks,

01:00:17.540 --> 01:00:22.850
all identical except for the
disposition of the buildings

01:00:22.850 --> 01:00:24.240
on them.

01:00:24.240 --> 01:00:29.180
So there was a grid system laid
out over an extensive area.

01:00:29.180 --> 01:00:34.760
It could continue
without disruption.

01:00:34.760 --> 01:00:42.200
Roads were 20 meters, 35
meters, or 50 meters wide.

01:00:42.200 --> 01:00:45.720
There was six cubic meters
of space per person.

01:00:45.720 --> 01:00:52.820
It was double the middle
income level at the time.

01:00:52.820 --> 01:00:57.950
It was part of Cerda that
was extremely rational.

01:00:57.950 --> 01:01:02.930
That formula that is on
the left is his formula

01:01:02.930 --> 01:01:15.770
for the width of the road, x
being the side of the block,

01:01:15.770 --> 01:01:18.440
2b being the width
of the street,

01:01:18.440 --> 01:01:21.090
f being the depth of
the building site,

01:01:21.090 --> 01:01:24.350
v being the number of
inhabitants per house,

01:01:24.350 --> 01:01:30.440
p equals the squared
meters size per person,

01:01:30.440 --> 01:01:33.650
d equals the height
of the facade,

01:01:33.650 --> 01:01:39.170
all rationally
calculated to produce it.

01:01:39.170 --> 01:01:41.910
The detail of the
formula is not important.

01:01:41.910 --> 01:01:45.260
It's nonsense, but
it shows something

01:01:45.260 --> 01:01:50.170
about the mind of a person who--

01:01:50.170 --> 01:01:53.860
what's going on in his mind?

01:01:53.860 --> 01:01:55.420
He's trained as an engineer.

01:01:55.420 --> 01:02:00.130
He's worked in cities
all over Spain.

01:02:03.100 --> 01:02:06.670
He returns to Barcelona,
spends his efforts

01:02:06.670 --> 01:02:10.705
documenting poverty,
then emerges with a plan.

01:02:14.510 --> 01:02:17.440
There's an interesting
side story to this.

01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:26.890
The critics and writers about
the ensanche in Barcelona

01:02:26.890 --> 01:02:29.860
were extraordinarily
loyal to the Barcelona

01:02:29.860 --> 01:02:36.640
and to Ildefons Cerda, who is
considered a national hero.

01:02:36.640 --> 01:02:42.520
By the way, the reason the
city chose Cerda's plan

01:02:42.520 --> 01:02:46.345
over Trias's plan was because
of pressure from Madrid.

01:02:50.550 --> 01:02:53.130
Cerda in his years
in Madrid working

01:02:53.130 --> 01:02:56.610
for the national militia
had made friends,

01:02:56.610 --> 01:03:02.610
and his radical plan
was forced on Barcelona.

01:03:02.610 --> 01:03:07.940
Now Barcelona cannot be
happier about the plan.

01:03:07.940 --> 01:03:10.560
Cerda is a great hero.

01:03:10.560 --> 01:03:15.090
There's an aspect of
Cerda which comes through

01:03:15.090 --> 01:03:17.670
not from Barcelonans.

01:03:17.670 --> 01:03:21.480
I don't know the Barcelona
literature extensively,

01:03:21.480 --> 01:03:25.740
but a man has recently
written a book

01:03:25.740 --> 01:03:31.830
pointing out that Cerda belonged
to a small group of people,

01:03:31.830 --> 01:03:37.890
intellectuals in Barcelona who
were attracted to socialism.

01:03:40.950 --> 01:03:44.460
Amongst their members was
a man called [INAUDIBLE],,

01:03:44.460 --> 01:03:48.810
who was one of the designers
of the modern submarine.

01:03:48.810 --> 01:03:50.635
Strange people.

01:03:50.635 --> 01:03:51.135
Poets.

01:03:53.840 --> 01:03:57.440
Apparently, they were
very influenced by French

01:03:57.440 --> 01:04:02.730
intellectual utopianist called
Etienne Cabet, C-A-B-E-T,

01:04:02.730 --> 01:04:07.550
who wrote a book called
A Voyage to Icaria.

01:04:13.720 --> 01:04:22.420
Cabet proposed in his ideal
city a center with the capital,

01:04:22.420 --> 01:04:25.210
and then an equal
distribution of space

01:04:25.210 --> 01:04:29.180
every 360 degrees
around the center.

01:04:32.980 --> 01:04:36.970
Cabet worked in the
British Museum reading room

01:04:36.970 --> 01:04:38.830
just like Marx did.

01:04:38.830 --> 01:04:40.430
I don't think they
knew each other.

01:04:40.430 --> 01:04:43.750
They were years apart.

01:04:43.750 --> 01:04:50.170
Cabet insisted that
the United States

01:04:50.170 --> 01:04:56.708
was the place to build a
utopia, as many Europeans did.

01:04:56.708 --> 01:04:57.625
Fourier, for instance.

01:05:01.810 --> 01:05:05.830
There's a paradox about Fourier
and the Fourierist community

01:05:05.830 --> 01:05:09.760
in the United States, but that's
for another class when you talk

01:05:09.760 --> 01:05:14.140
about utopianism next week.

01:05:14.140 --> 01:05:21.010
Cabet bought land in New Orleans
and took 79 Cabetians with him

01:05:21.010 --> 01:05:23.650
to New Orleans.

01:05:23.650 --> 01:05:25.000
They hated New Orleans.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:26.800
The climate was awful.

01:05:26.800 --> 01:05:30.490
They didn't know anything
about the land they bought.

01:05:30.490 --> 01:05:35.180
They were sold a piece of
land which was really bad.

01:05:35.180 --> 01:05:40.280
They moved north to Nauvoo,
N-A-U-V-O-O, Illinois,

01:05:40.280 --> 01:05:45.730
which is one of the sequence
of places that the Mormons

01:05:45.730 --> 01:05:50.440
capitalized on on the trek from
the East Coast to Salt Lake

01:05:50.440 --> 01:05:51.670
City.

01:05:51.670 --> 01:05:56.410
They took over Nauvoo,
Illinois, which didn't succeed.

01:05:56.410 --> 01:05:59.620
[INAUDIBLE],, for instance,
wanted to join them.

01:05:59.620 --> 01:06:05.170
He wrote to Etienne Cabet, but
Cabet had died in the meantime,

01:06:05.170 --> 01:06:07.870
and the whole enterprise
suffered terribly.

01:06:10.910 --> 01:06:18.320
How much of this Cerda knew
or how much of this Cerda

01:06:18.320 --> 01:06:23.180
was interested in is
difficult to know.

01:06:23.180 --> 01:06:27.170
He remains an enigmatic
figure but a man

01:06:27.170 --> 01:06:31.910
who achieved enormous amounts.

01:06:31.910 --> 01:06:39.800
His plan was built, built
to a certain degree.

01:06:42.950 --> 01:06:54.800
The grid system was maintained,
but the amount and disposition

01:06:54.800 --> 01:06:57.730
of this site changed.

01:06:57.730 --> 01:07:02.570
It's in the diagram on one
of the pages I gave you.

01:07:02.570 --> 01:07:11.000
We'll see Cerda's wish to have
a fluctuating system, where

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:14.960
the site was either occupied
by two buildings, three

01:07:14.960 --> 01:07:20.600
buildings, or four completely
enclosed by four buildings.

01:07:20.600 --> 01:07:23.480
For Cerda, the
height of the facade

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:28.730
was to be limited
to three floors.

01:07:28.730 --> 01:07:32.940
There were no elevators
in existence yet.

01:07:32.940 --> 01:07:33.440
Anyway.

01:07:41.840 --> 01:07:44.930
The height of the blocks
were 16 meters maximum.

01:07:44.930 --> 01:07:47.600
That's a ground floor
and three floors,

01:07:47.600 --> 01:07:49.640
and the maximum
coverage was 50%.

01:07:56.220 --> 01:08:05.060
Cerda had very little to do with
the application of the plan.

01:08:08.520 --> 01:08:13.080
Here there was no accompanying
policy to make sure

01:08:13.080 --> 01:08:14.400
who lived in the space.

01:08:21.229 --> 01:08:23.270
The number of
devices which we've

01:08:23.270 --> 01:08:28.460
invented since Cerda's time to
make sure that we have a mixed

01:08:28.460 --> 01:08:33.500
population in space sometimes
as simply as putting

01:08:33.500 --> 01:08:38.189
a percentage, 15% on new
development in Cambridge,

01:08:38.189 --> 01:08:41.990
Massachusetts to be allocated
to affordable housing

01:08:41.990 --> 01:08:45.439
as a part of any
building of new housing.

01:08:45.439 --> 01:08:46.760
There was nothing like that.

01:08:46.760 --> 01:08:51.350
Cerda envisioned an
equal spatial plan,

01:08:51.350 --> 01:08:55.370
and isotropic plan
spatially, but he

01:08:55.370 --> 01:08:59.840
didn't understand how to get
an isotropic distribution

01:08:59.840 --> 01:09:02.569
of population.

01:09:02.569 --> 01:09:08.029
He envisioned baker's living
next to bankers, communities

01:09:08.029 --> 01:09:11.240
within this grid, each
with their own school,

01:09:11.240 --> 01:09:15.109
and so on, and so on, and so
on, but he played little role

01:09:15.109 --> 01:09:20.120
that I know in the
execution of the plan.

01:09:20.120 --> 01:09:24.529
There's a great--
oh, I've got to rush.

01:09:24.529 --> 01:09:27.310
There's a great paradox here.

01:09:27.310 --> 01:09:32.120
Over time, ensanche
has become developed

01:09:32.120 --> 01:09:33.469
at a much greater density.

01:09:39.450 --> 01:09:47.029
Coverage was increased from
50% to 70%, even more than 70%.

01:09:47.029 --> 01:09:52.729
Height was increased
to 24 meters.

01:09:52.729 --> 01:09:56.370
The volume of Cerda's
plan was supposed

01:09:56.370 --> 01:10:00.430
to be 67,000 meters squared.

01:10:00.430 --> 01:10:04.620
The 1958 volume of what
has being built on his plan

01:10:04.620 --> 01:10:17.960
is over three times as
much, 290,000 square meters.

01:10:17.960 --> 01:10:23.440
The paradox is that if you go
down the [INAUDIBLE],, which

01:10:23.440 --> 01:10:27.820
is the great road built through
the ensanche, this great avenue

01:10:27.820 --> 01:10:31.060
which I'll show you
an image of, you

01:10:31.060 --> 01:10:34.720
can feel the pedestrian volume.

01:10:34.720 --> 01:10:40.013
He allowed five meters
of pedestrian width

01:10:40.013 --> 01:10:40.930
throughout the scheme.

01:10:44.450 --> 01:10:48.260
There's an intensity of urban
intensity in this area, which

01:10:48.260 --> 01:10:49.925
is part of its charm.

01:10:57.370 --> 01:11:02.860
Cerda's plan was so
pro forma in a sense

01:11:02.860 --> 01:11:05.260
that it allowed so
many things to happen

01:11:05.260 --> 01:11:09.850
after his time, such as the
increase of density and still,

01:11:09.850 --> 01:11:14.530
except for automobile traffic,
able to cope with the world.

01:11:14.530 --> 01:11:17.297
The fact that he made
sideways sidewalks that

01:11:17.297 --> 01:11:20.320
were all that wide
was an indication

01:11:20.320 --> 01:11:26.710
of some thinking about
the advent of density.

01:11:26.710 --> 01:11:37.130
He didn't include techniques
which could frustrate

01:11:37.130 --> 01:11:40.580
subsequent development.

01:11:40.580 --> 01:11:42.770
What happened is
that, as you'll see--

01:11:42.770 --> 01:11:46.790
let's look at the pictures now.

01:11:46.790 --> 01:11:51.470
The Danube, and Vienna
below on the southern border

01:11:51.470 --> 01:11:52.580
of the Danube next.

01:11:56.070 --> 01:12:06.570
The walls as walkways and
pedestrian perambulation zones

01:12:06.570 --> 01:12:08.310
prior to their being removed.

01:12:08.310 --> 01:12:10.255
The glacis on the right.

01:12:10.255 --> 01:12:10.755
Next.

01:12:14.160 --> 01:12:17.520
The clear space
after the walls have

01:12:17.520 --> 01:12:21.390
been taken down, and the
filling in of this space

01:12:21.390 --> 01:12:23.490
with a single spine.

01:12:23.490 --> 01:12:24.540
Next.

01:12:24.540 --> 01:12:35.680
The parliament, town
hall, university, theater,

01:12:35.680 --> 01:12:37.870
accommodation.

01:12:37.870 --> 01:12:41.290
That's Hitler's drawing of
the parliament, by the way.

01:12:41.290 --> 01:12:42.792
Not bad.

01:12:42.792 --> 01:12:45.635
He should've got into
architecture school.

01:12:45.635 --> 01:12:46.135
Next.

01:12:50.530 --> 01:12:54.200
The medieval town hall,
which still exists.

01:12:54.200 --> 01:12:54.700
Next.

01:12:57.900 --> 01:13:01.140
A [INAUDIBLE],, an
apartment building.

01:13:01.140 --> 01:13:11.610
Large blocks, large volume, and
the phenomenon [? again in ?]

01:13:11.610 --> 01:13:16.830
[? the ?] facade of decorating
the facade with sculpture.

01:13:16.830 --> 01:13:18.870
This is not a flat facade.

01:13:18.870 --> 01:13:19.370
Next.

01:13:23.160 --> 01:13:26.670
The entrance to the
apartment building

01:13:26.670 --> 01:13:40.500
has this zone of almost
regal or royal pertinence.

01:13:40.500 --> 01:13:45.390
Again, these decorative
system which is open and free,

01:13:45.390 --> 01:13:54.840
giving spatial quality to
the extrinsic experience.

01:13:54.840 --> 01:13:57.595
Next.

01:13:57.595 --> 01:14:03.570
And Camillo Sitte, a
critique of the what

01:14:03.570 --> 01:14:06.510
he calls the turbine
plaza, a plaza in which you

01:14:06.510 --> 01:14:08.395
enter and move--

01:14:08.395 --> 01:14:11.550
a plaza which is
correctly organized,

01:14:11.550 --> 01:14:16.770
where you enter and leave
only in special places.

01:14:16.770 --> 01:14:19.530
In the center of
the plaza is a space

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:25.750
for emotional contemplation.

01:14:25.750 --> 01:14:34.620
His proposal in the shaded
zones for recreating a proper

01:14:34.620 --> 01:14:38.460
appearance in front of the
[? votive ?] [? church, ?]

01:14:38.460 --> 01:14:43.920
breaking down the openness,
which is credited to actors

01:14:43.920 --> 01:14:45.180
called [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:45.180 --> 01:14:49.860
He was afraid of open space,
demarcating space in relation

01:14:49.860 --> 01:14:52.300
to particular buildings.

01:14:52.300 --> 01:14:52.800
Next.

01:14:55.570 --> 01:15:00.520
Otto Wagner's impression for
the expansion of the city

01:15:00.520 --> 01:15:04.120
is a series of zones
that articulated

01:15:04.120 --> 01:15:08.240
by a kind of expansionist line.

01:15:08.240 --> 01:15:13.300
Here is his design
for one of the--

01:15:13.300 --> 01:15:21.070
sorry-- or one of the proposed
extension expansion areas.

01:15:21.070 --> 01:15:23.590
Next.

01:15:23.590 --> 01:15:28.000
His preoccupation with
designing industrial buildings.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:31.870
This is sluice building
on the Danube canal.

01:15:31.870 --> 01:15:34.840
You can see these are--

01:15:34.840 --> 01:15:40.450
can you see the wavelike
decoration up on the right?

01:15:40.450 --> 01:15:45.430
This is a man who's carrying
a kind of hybrid system

01:15:45.430 --> 01:15:50.350
in his head, on the one hand,
wanting to make something as

01:15:50.350 --> 01:15:52.940
decidedly modern as possible.

01:15:52.940 --> 01:16:00.760
On the other, decorating it
with a frieze facade decoration.

01:16:00.760 --> 01:16:07.440
His subway stop, the Karlsplatz.

01:16:07.440 --> 01:16:07.940
Next.

01:16:11.530 --> 01:16:17.190
His buildings in the railways
[INAUDIBLE] new railway system.

01:16:17.190 --> 01:16:21.830
At the same time, this is
a competition entry of his.

01:16:21.830 --> 01:16:24.490
I can't remember what
the building was.

01:16:24.490 --> 01:16:27.970
I think the Academy
of Fine Arts,

01:16:27.970 --> 01:16:31.150
and this is the Postal
Savings Bank building,

01:16:31.150 --> 01:16:34.750
where the decorative
system is on the facade

01:16:34.750 --> 01:16:38.755
in between the regular
machine-like windows.

01:16:38.755 --> 01:16:39.255
Next.

01:16:42.910 --> 01:16:47.630
I didn't have time to go
into this in greater detail,

01:16:47.630 --> 01:16:54.730
but this is Joseph Hoffman's
work in the industrial design

01:16:54.730 --> 01:17:00.880
sector in the great
advances in modern design,

01:17:00.880 --> 01:17:04.370
using new materials.

01:17:04.370 --> 01:17:11.170
This is a list of the
theater performances

01:17:11.170 --> 01:17:15.875
for the weekend in Vienna.

01:17:15.875 --> 01:17:16.375
Next.

01:17:18.940 --> 01:17:25.930
Mahler's great Symphony
Number Six, and, to my mind,

01:17:25.930 --> 01:17:29.770
greatest book of
Freud's interpretation

01:17:29.770 --> 01:17:33.075
of dreams in 1911.

01:17:33.075 --> 01:17:33.575
Next.

01:17:37.170 --> 01:17:41.265
Karl Marx-Hof and some
of the other hof blocks.

01:17:45.040 --> 01:17:47.500
Karl Marx-Hof on the left.

01:17:47.500 --> 01:17:50.450
I think it's 1 and
1/2 kilometers long.

01:17:50.450 --> 01:17:50.950
Next.

01:17:54.900 --> 01:18:00.765
The abiding preoccupation
with sculpture and a flag.

01:18:08.700 --> 01:18:10.335
These arches are not entrances.

01:18:10.335 --> 01:18:13.530
They're zones of penetration.

01:18:13.530 --> 01:18:15.570
These are the entrance zones.

01:18:15.570 --> 01:18:19.050
Again, they decorate.

01:18:19.050 --> 01:18:22.650
Apartments are very small.

01:18:22.650 --> 01:18:26.610
Once when I was
visiting this building,

01:18:26.610 --> 01:18:30.390
the taxi driver had lived
in this Karl Marx-Hof,

01:18:30.390 --> 01:18:32.250
and he said he left
because he couldn't

01:18:32.250 --> 01:18:36.930
swing a cat in his apartment.

01:18:36.930 --> 01:18:38.793
Those were his words.

01:18:38.793 --> 01:18:42.657
[LAUGHTER]

01:18:42.657 --> 01:18:47.790
An enormously powerful
manifestation.

01:18:47.790 --> 01:18:52.050
Michael Graves must have
looked at this architecture

01:18:52.050 --> 01:18:56.590
to gain some inspiration
for his buildings.

01:18:56.590 --> 01:18:57.090
Next.

01:19:00.100 --> 01:19:02.190
Barcelona.

01:19:02.190 --> 01:19:08.740
Look at the size of the ensanche
compared to the old city,

01:19:08.740 --> 01:19:12.640
and you can imagine what Cerda
would have done to Paris,

01:19:12.640 --> 01:19:13.710
the [INAUDIBLE] of Paris.

01:19:21.280 --> 01:19:25.150
It's worth spending
10 minutes to talk

01:19:25.150 --> 01:19:29.050
about that as an
alternative model for what

01:19:29.050 --> 01:19:34.130
the post-modern Paris
competition's entries did.

01:19:34.130 --> 01:19:34.630
Next.

01:19:37.260 --> 01:19:41.820
Cerda's vision, a
three-floor set of blocks

01:19:41.820 --> 01:19:45.660
differentiating
between two blocks

01:19:45.660 --> 01:19:49.030
which only had one arm
on them, others which

01:19:49.030 --> 01:19:53.420
had two buildings, some which
had three buildings, some where

01:19:53.420 --> 01:19:55.750
the square was enclosed.

01:19:55.750 --> 01:20:00.420
What was actually built is
represented on the right--

01:20:00.420 --> 01:20:04.590
enclosed space in the
center, not public space,

01:20:04.590 --> 01:20:10.260
but ambiguous space, sometimes
space which was taken over

01:20:10.260 --> 01:20:14.550
by residents, sometimes space
which was made into parking

01:20:14.550 --> 01:20:18.870
lots, sometimes space
which is just dilapidated,

01:20:18.870 --> 01:20:22.830
but no resolution of the
internal space [? of a ?]

01:20:22.830 --> 01:20:25.465
consolidated four-sided block.

01:20:25.465 --> 01:20:25.965
Next.

01:20:29.270 --> 01:20:31.490
You can see some of
the interior of the--

01:20:37.130 --> 01:20:41.140
there's a difference
between making Karl Marx-Hof

01:20:41.140 --> 01:20:45.820
interior space as a space for
the community with clinics,

01:20:45.820 --> 01:20:50.980
shops, medical facilities,
schools, and so on as

01:20:50.980 --> 01:20:52.090
a concept.

01:20:52.090 --> 01:20:57.640
This is a concept which enclosed
a block in order to galvanize

01:20:57.640 --> 01:21:03.280
the quality of the street,
to increase density,

01:21:03.280 --> 01:21:09.455
but left the whole
completely unavailable.

01:21:09.455 --> 01:21:09.955
Next.

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:19.150
Cerda's plan calls
for the blocks

01:21:19.150 --> 01:21:21.730
to be truncated on the corners.

01:21:21.730 --> 01:21:27.790
Here you can see an intersection
of the four corners,

01:21:27.790 --> 01:21:35.710
leaving a messy transportation
intersection problem there.

01:21:35.710 --> 01:21:39.460
One of the arguments made
by the Barcelonans today

01:21:39.460 --> 01:21:42.640
is that this creates
another facade,

01:21:42.640 --> 01:21:45.880
and each of these small
square intersections

01:21:45.880 --> 01:21:51.275
have unique facades
facing onto them.

01:21:51.275 --> 01:21:51.775
Next.

01:21:54.660 --> 01:22:02.190
[INAUDIBLE],, the medieval public
walk, and the [INAUDIBLE],,

01:22:02.190 --> 01:22:06.030
this great avenue which
links to the town of Gracia

01:22:06.030 --> 01:22:07.775
in the hills.

01:22:07.775 --> 01:22:08.275
Next.

01:22:13.380 --> 01:22:17.250
The [INAUDIBLE]
[? guardian. ?] Sorry.

01:22:17.250 --> 01:22:21.470
[INAUDIBLE] on the left, the
[INAUDIBLE] on the right.

01:22:21.470 --> 01:22:21.970
Next.

01:22:27.520 --> 01:22:33.730
A great unfinished
cathedral, an attempt

01:22:33.730 --> 01:22:38.230
to modernize the ensanche.

01:22:38.230 --> 01:22:38.730
Next.

01:22:44.180 --> 01:22:46.640
The Barcelona Games
is the only games

01:22:46.640 --> 01:22:51.440
that position the
center of the city

01:22:51.440 --> 01:22:56.390
as central to the four sides--

01:22:56.390 --> 01:23:02.786
the [INAUDIBLE] side on the
top left, the [INAUDIBLE] side

01:23:02.786 --> 01:23:11.840
for the athletes' housing.

01:23:11.840 --> 01:23:20.840
Of all the Olympic sites, from
Munich, to Tokyo, to Sydney,

01:23:20.840 --> 01:23:25.760
to Melbourne, London, and
so on, none of [INAUDIBLE]

01:23:25.760 --> 01:23:31.910
incorporated the proposition
within the central city system.

01:23:31.910 --> 01:23:32.410
Next.

01:23:36.770 --> 01:23:40.550
Two post-Cerda propositions.

01:23:40.550 --> 01:23:42.530
Could you just focus
this one please?

01:23:42.530 --> 01:23:44.630
Thank you.

01:23:44.630 --> 01:23:47.390
This is Corbusier's
and a group called

01:23:47.390 --> 01:23:53.360
[INAUDIBLE],, a modern version
of the extension of the Cerda

01:23:53.360 --> 01:23:55.200
system.

01:23:55.200 --> 01:23:59.430
The streets are
gone, or they ignored

01:23:59.430 --> 01:24:08.190
the [INAUDIBLE] system of
Corbusier's engaged in housing.

01:24:08.190 --> 01:24:10.480
There's a huge
amount of open space

01:24:10.480 --> 01:24:14.700
which is not allocated
to anybody in particular.

01:24:14.700 --> 01:24:19.810
One prefers the scheme
on the left infinitely.

01:24:19.810 --> 01:24:25.840
A crazy man, Léon Krier,
saying that the problem with

01:24:25.840 --> 01:24:31.910
Cerda's plan is the 113
meter size is too large.

01:24:31.910 --> 01:24:38.740
Krier has a dislike of
anything continuous,

01:24:38.740 --> 01:24:43.060
so he suggests that
the clock be broken up

01:24:43.060 --> 01:24:52.360
into four modules
of 25 meters each,

01:24:52.360 --> 01:24:55.330
where he believed
the market is for all

01:24:55.330 --> 01:24:59.590
of the shopping on
these little corners,

01:24:59.590 --> 01:25:04.420
and the confusion caused
by creating as many corners

01:25:04.420 --> 01:25:06.055
as you like.

01:25:06.055 --> 01:25:10.030
Léon Krier should visit Tel Aviv
and see what happens when you

01:25:10.030 --> 01:25:15.490
subdivide blocks into
two smaller distance.

01:25:15.490 --> 01:25:22.070
It's a silly diagram, but
two examples of post-Cerda

01:25:22.070 --> 01:25:22.570
thinking.

01:25:28.510 --> 01:25:30.015
I think that's a lot.

01:25:30.015 --> 01:25:30.890
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:25:30.890 --> 01:25:33.190
JULIAN BEINART: Oh, sorry.

01:25:33.190 --> 01:25:35.350
The idea of expanding from--

01:25:35.350 --> 01:25:40.810
by leaving the center allowed
an expanding outwards.

01:25:40.810 --> 01:25:43.870
This is Antonelli's
plan for Torino.

01:25:43.870 --> 01:25:46.720
That is Custer's
plan for Madrid.

01:25:46.720 --> 01:25:48.550
Next.

01:25:48.550 --> 01:25:51.010
This is [INAUDIBLE]
plan for [INAUDIBLE],,

01:25:51.010 --> 01:25:54.580
and this is
[? Kritanthis's ?] plan--

01:25:54.580 --> 01:25:57.730
[? Krianthis-Schubert's ?]
plan for Athens.

01:25:57.730 --> 01:26:01.330
All suggest in the
dark gray that you

01:26:01.330 --> 01:26:04.630
maintain the core of
the city, take away

01:26:04.630 --> 01:26:11.320
the walls if necessary, and
produce a free zone outside.

01:26:11.320 --> 01:26:13.750
Next.

01:26:13.750 --> 01:26:17.050
Here in the small town
of Altamura in Apulia,

01:26:17.050 --> 01:26:20.830
you see the system
operating in a small town.

01:26:20.830 --> 01:26:26.170
Radiating outwards are
gates to the old city.

01:26:31.280 --> 01:26:33.650
I haven't got time to
go into the detail.

01:26:33.650 --> 01:26:39.110
Here you see a grid
system employed almost

01:26:39.110 --> 01:26:46.610
throughout the surroundings
of the existing walled city.

01:26:46.610 --> 01:26:49.220
If the walls are
taken away or replaced

01:26:49.220 --> 01:26:52.040
by a boulevard
surrounding the city,

01:26:52.040 --> 01:26:56.210
nothing like the boulevard
of the Ringstrasse.

01:26:56.210 --> 01:26:58.040
OK.

01:26:58.040 --> 01:27:03.880
Sorry it's so rushed, but the
world is full of information.